            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr Ferdinand Mueller</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Government Botanist in Victoria</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Revered Sir,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The German Club of Victoria, in the general meeting of 26 January of this year, decided unanimously to receive you as honorary member of the Club.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We are unable to give a greater proof of our deeply felt respect, and you are the first, to whom this Club has granted this honorable distinction.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By indefatigable endeavour and noble zeal for science you have, in the great field of botany, added your name to that of those men of science, to whom it was granted not only to penetrate and encompass science, but also to expand it. On Australia's impassable mountain ranges, in swamps and barren deserts, where man penetrates but rarely, with a tenacity, that can only be inspired by and draw strength from a true love of science, subjected to all kinds of privations and with bold contempt of dangers, you searched for earth's unknown products. Australia's flora, which you enriched with many names, will remember you with gratitude, and botanical history will record your name with distinction in the line of Linné's worthiest disciples.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Such great merits are all the more gladly acknowledged, when — as with you — they are clothed in the mantle of amiable modesty and unassuming selflessness. We agree gladly with the view of that English savant, who says of you: 'Mueller's scientific ability is surpassed only by his modesty.'<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See footnotes to J. Macadam to M, February 1857 where Henry Barkly attributes this statement to William Hooker.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Accept these lines as the feeble expression of that respect and veneration, which we feel for your true scientific endeavour and your noble character, and do not regard it as empty words, when we say:</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; text-align: center; "
               xml:lang="en">'We are proud to call you one of us.'</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The certificate was presented to M on 11 June 1857 at a meeting of the German Club at the Criterion Hotel, Melbourne. Some 120 members of the Club were present, and speeches were made and songs sung to mark the occasion (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Der Kosmopolit</seg> [Melbourne], 16 June 1857, p. 235). See also M to W. Hooker, 21 June 1857.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Not all of the signatories have been identified; those that have been are listed in the biographical register.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
